dns-leak-server — Setup Guide

Prerequisites
─────────────
  - Debian/Ubuntu host
  - Root or sudo access
  - Domain with NS delegation to this server

Host Dependencies
─────────────────
  apt-get update
  apt-get install -y openssl

  curl -fsSL https://get.docker.com -o get-docker.sh
  sh get-docker.sh

  # Free port 53 (if systemd-resolved is running)
  systemctl stop systemd-resolved
  systemctl disable systemd-resolved
  rm -f /etc/resolv.conf
  echo "nameserver 1.1.1.1" > /etc/resolv.conf
  chattr +i /etc/resolv.conf

DNS Records (Cloudflare)
────────────────────────
  dns-leak-server.phantom.tc    NS      ns-leak-1.phantom.tc
  ns-leak-1.phantom.tc          A       <SERVER_IPV4>
  ns-leak-1.phantom.tc          AAAA    <SERVER_IPV6>

Configuration
─────────────
  cp .env.example .env

  # Edit .env:
  #   DNS_ZONE=dns-leak-server.phantom.tc
  #   NS_HOST=ns-leak-1.phantom.tc
  #   SERVER_IPV4=<your ipv4>
  #   SERVER_IPV6=<your ipv6>
  #   TOKEN_TTL=30
  #   ACME_EMAIL=<your email>

Setup
─────
  tools/prod.sh setup

  This will:
    1. Generate shared secret (secrets/shared_secret)
    2. Build ACME container
    3. Issue wildcard TLS certificate via Let's Encrypt DNS-01
    4. Store certificate in secrets/certs/

Start
─────
  tools/prod.sh up

Management
──────────
  tools/prod.sh up          Start
  tools/prod.sh down        Stop
  tools/prod.sh restart     Restart
  tools/prod.sh rebuild     Build from scratch
  tools/prod.sh logs        Follow logs
  tools/prod.sh status      Show status
  tools/prod.sh shell       Open shell in container
  tools/prod.sh exec <cmd>  Execute command in container

Certificate Renewal
───────────────────
  tools/prod.sh renew-cert

  Auto-renewal via cron (monthly, 1st day at 03:00):
    apt-get install -y cron
    systemctl enable cron
    systemctl start cron
    crontab -e
    # Add:
    0 3 1 * * /opt/dns-leak-server/tools/prod.sh renew-cert >> /var/log/dns-leak-cert-renew.log 2>&1

Verify
──────
  # DNS response
  dig @<SERVER_IPV4> test-test-0000000000.dns-leak-server.phantom.tc A

  # HTTPS response (use valid HMAC token from worker)
  curl -s https://<token>.dns-leak-server.phantom.tc/